text: Just got back from seeing a "pre-screening" and I really like this movie.  It really captures your attention and the characters draw you in.  I would give it an 8/10 and liked it much better than Call Me By Your Name.  I found the ending nice but thought it was a little exaggerated like the film Grease (Danny and Sandy) with everyone all happy at the end that the 2 were finally together in a tacky sing-y/dance-y way.   Other than a Hollywood sweet but still sappy ending it was worth the money and the message it sends about inclusiveness, acceptance and forgiveness is a message worth imparting on a world that needs to make room for one another with a supportive embrace despite differences.  If I were to change one thing about the end it would be to make the unification of Simon and Blue more about them alone and not with their peers cheering them on. Ok that's my review.

text: I watched the movie recently and I noticed that a lot of things in the movie were different from the book. For example, Simon actually has an older sister named Alice. They completely cut Alice from the movie even though she plays a relatively big part in Simon's life. Also, in the book, they do Oliver! instead of Cabaret. Leah is, in fact, in love with Nick and not Simon. Blue's email address is the same as it is in the book, but Simon's is different. In the book, Simon's email is hourtohour.notetonote@gmail.com. If you want to know more, I suggest reading the book/seeing the movie for yourself. I'm not complaining, though. I absolutely loved both the movie and the book and to see these characters brought to life was amazing!  Love,         Janet :)

text: I've watched this movie several times. There were some things that I wished had occurred differently. I'm curious if others feel the same way.  While his friends were rightfully upset with Simon for what he did; once they learned about him being blackmailed by Martin their reaction ticked me off. The "what's that have to do with us" really annoyed me. You would have thought that they would have cut him some slack given the situation he was in. They only thought about themselves. Next, in the cafeteria, none of his friends came to his defense in the cafeteria with what those two jerks did. Not even that could get them to put their hurt feelings aside. They didn't seem to be feeling any empathy with what Simon was dealing with. I would have liked to have seen at least one person in that school, in the cafeteria scene after Simon was outed, to have had the courage to walk up to Simon's table to sit down and eat with him. No, I'm not Blue, but I think what was done to you was really shitty. What did they do on that big adventure when the movie ended? Is there any one, other than myself, who would have liked to have seen the two cafeteria jerks get forced to do something that would have been really humiliating to them like having to scrub all the toilets and urinals in the men's bathrooms clean with a tooth brush as their detention punishment? It's obvious by their joke of an apology to Simon and Ethan they truly weren't sorry. I'm curious to see what others think on these thoughts.
